subsection.example:
Consider the system,
\begin{array}{rrrrr} 2x \amp + y \amp - z \amp = \amp -2 \\ \amp 3y \amp + z \amp = \amp 10 \\ \amp \amp 3z \amp = \amp 3 \end{array}
Notice that the last equation has only one variable, and so can be solved to determine the value of z. In this case, 3z = 3 implies that z = 1. In other words, if (x,y,z) is a solution to this system, it must have z=1 in order to satisfy the 3rd equation. Then, we can work backwards and determine the remaining values. First, this value of z can be used to solve for y in the second equation. If z = 1, then 3y + 1 = 10, and solving for y gives y = 3. Finally, the values of y and z can be used to solve for x, using the first equation. If z = 1 and y = 3, then 2x + 3 - 1 = -2, and solving for x gives x = -2. Thus, this system has a single unique solution, (-2,3,1).

Consider the system,

    \begin{array}{rrrrr}
    2x \amp + y \amp + z \amp = \amp 1 \\
    4x \amp + y \amp \amp = \amp -2 \\
    -2x \amp + 2y \amp + z \amp = \amp 7
    \end{array}

We want to convert this system into triangular form, from which it will be easy to solve. To do this, we need to eliminate the variables below the main diagonal, i.e. eliminate x from the 2nd and 3rd equation and y from the 3rd equation. To do this, first, add -2 times the 1st equation to the 2nd equation, and add the 1st equation to the 3rd equation. This results in the equivalent system,

    \begin{array}{rrrrr}
    2x \amp + y \amp + z \amp = \amp 1 \\
    \amp -y \amp -2z \amp = \amp -4 \\
    \amp 3y \amp + 2z \amp = \amp 8
    \end{array}

Notice that this involved choosing appropriate multiples of the 1st equation to add to the other equations. Next, we use the 2nd equation to eliminate y in the 3rd equation, by adding 3 times the 2nd equation to the 3rd equation. This is results in the system,

    \begin{array}{rrrrr}
    2x \amp + y \amp + z \amp = \amp 1 \\
    \amp -y \amp -2z \amp = \amp -4 \\
    \amp \amp -4z \amp = \amp -4
    \end{array}

This system is in triangular form, so we can use back substitution. Solving for z, we get z = 1. Then, solving for y gives y = 2, and finally x = -1.
